node.text:
Bowmar Archery Grip Tape! 
I dive deep in this video going into everything that Levi and I have put into this grip tape for over a year. Our goal was to help create the most constant grip possible, and I truly believe we’ve done it. Our weather resistant tacky polymer grip CANT BE BEAT in wet or sweaty conditions. On top of that, our heavily researched, developed, and tested grip pattern is specifically designed for archers keeping your hand from sliding left or right and up and down. I’m beyond excited to bring this product to all us archers. We truly believe it’ll make a huge difference for all levels, both PRO and beginner on keeping a constant grip.
We have 11 different colors to choose from, if you’d like to order please click the link in our profile, we appreciate your support more than you know!

node.text: I made it back to civilization! Been out on the Alaska peninsula brown bear hunting for almost 2 weeks! I’m going to post day by day with how everything went down. First day, we went shed hunting out in the tundra. Thanks @drivenhunter for getting the last video. It sure was a great time!

node.text: This buck we knew well and I even hunted him back in 2019. He was ancient and by far the largest body deer I ever got on camera. With an estimated weight of over 300lbs! He disappeared on us after November 26 and now we know why. Sad to see such an old big buck go out like this. But at least we have closure to his story.

node.text: Got in on some spot and stalk action with the compound! Managed to get a shot at this beautiful old Lichtenstein hartebeest at 63 yards. My arrow flew true and hit him right in the heart. When we walked up to him, we couldn’t help but notice he was growing a 3rd horn out of his head 😳 super crazy and unique! This wraps up our trip in the selous! Now we’re heading to Maasai lands for part 2 of our trip. I’m having an adventure of a lifetime. We’ve captured everything on video, I love bringing you all along on these adventure bow hunts. I can’t wait for you all to see it. @bowmar_archery

node.text: The amount of respect I have for this animal cant be quantified. For a bull this mature to stay alive and live amongst lions, leopards, hyenas, disease, and other bulls  just shows you how tough and resilient they really are.  But at the end of the day, nothing dies of old age in the wild. At some point, the harsh reality sets in and Mother Nature turns into a brutal serial killer on the old, weak, and unable. As a hunter, it’s always my goal to go after the old and mature animals regardless the weapon I choose to use. What separates a mature Cape buffalo bull and a young bull  is the bosses. When they are young and immature the bosses will be soft, but once they fully mature the bosses turn solid. As you can see from the photos, he has fully hard bosses. I couldn’t be happier and more proud of this african beast. I can’t wait to share all these amazing experiences with you. We’ve captured every moment on camera and truly some of the most incredibly encounters after captured on video.

node.text: I did it! 100% wild free ranging Cape buffalo  with my homemade longbow! This is one of the proudest moments of my life and one of my greatest accomplishments as a bow hunter. I couldn’t be more proud of this shot! Under 20 yards face to face with a Cape buffalo and not folding under pressure, but instead, making the best shot of my life. Releasing that arrow and watching it hit that Cape buffalo perfectly right behind the shoulder, double lunging him was the most surreal moment I’ve ever had in the bush. I can’t begin to put into words how much this buffalo means to me. All I can say is, a 100% wild, 100% free ranging Tanzania Cape buffalo with hard bosses with a homemade bow is my Everest in hunting. Truly an achievement of a lifetime. The best part is, I got the whole hunt  on film! I can’t wait to share it with you.

node.text: THE MOMENT OF TRUTH! All the preparation, hard work, and relentless effort, all came down to this critical moment. We got inside 70 yards, then 50, then 30. Patiently we wait for the right second and made the move to get in closer, and close over the course of 20-30 mins going slow and low only moving when this big bull moved. We finally got to 18 yards from this beast totally undetected, I knew it was now or never, right when I was about to draw and shoot, he caught movement and lifted his head up starring right at me. My soul dropped, my adrenaline went through the roof. The danger got serious, and serious fast, but there was enough brush to break up my outline so he didn’t charge or run right away. Time felt like it stood still as we starred at each other for only a few seconds, but it felt like hours. I made the decision, I was going draw my homemade bow and take my shot if I could get to full draw slowly. He’s either going to charge or run, either way, this was my chance, this was my opportunity of a lifetime and I needed to make it count..

node.text: Getting close!! Making moves on these giant beasts. Getting to 50 is hard, but getting to 20 yards or less seems more and more impossible after every failed try. All we need is one in the right spot at the right time. I don’t need a giant, but he needs to be mature. Regardless the weapon I choose, I won’t shoot an immature animal.

node.text: There’s something extra special about holding a primitive weapon in Africa. The best part is our lead tracker “swaga” was a huge bow hunter himself except him and his tribe always used poison on their arrows to take down their game. He couldn’t believe I was using a longbow without poison. Haha He didn’t think a longbow could go deep enough into a buffalo to kill it. Then I handed him my bow and let him try and pull back this 110lb beast. His face when he drew the bow was so funny! He realized real quick this wasn’t any ordinary longbow. Surprisingly for his size he could draw the bow back pretty far, I was impressed! He went on to tell hunting stories in his swahili language of bow hunts he had been on. Even tho I didn’t understand, I knew we were bow brothers, purely based off his excitement about the bow and arrow. I love being in company of people that share the same passion bow hunting. We’re all working hard to make this happen. We’ve gotten close, just not close enough.

node.text: I’ve been hunting back and forth hunting with the compound and with the homemade stick bow. Getting a Cape buffalo with a bow I made will be my Everest in hunting. For me, this would be the ultimate stick bow accomplishment. The pure size and toughness of this animal is a massive challenging, but then you add in the small detail that it wants to kill you. They call Cape buffalo “Black Death” for a reason. With the stick bow you have to get inside that danger zone get inside 20 yards to assure penetration and accuracy. Getting this close and successfully killing Black Death with a homemade bow will challenge me beyond the hippo, beyond my biggest buck, beyond any bow hunting situation I’ve ever been in. Wish me luck. #bowhunter #wild

node.text: When the hippo went into the deep pool and died, someone had to go into the croc waters to loop rope around his head so we could pull him out. The trackers would have done it first, but I wanted it to be me, it had to be me. So I went in the croc waters first and started feeling around until I found my totally submerged bull. Once I found him, I moved to his head and pulled it up to put a rope around it. Once I got the rope around his head we thought the truck would be able to pull it out, but the bull was too heavy. It took 2.5 hours before we finally figured out a way to get the bull out of the water. It is incomprehensible just how big this bull is. The amount of meat on this bull would be equivalent to around 60 whitetail buck’s meat. It’s just insane that an animal this size can be killed with just a bow and an arrow.

node.text: You can see that huge chunk missing out of his face. That’s from fighting another bull and that other bull’s tusk Pierced his armor and took off a huge chunk of skin. We think this injury was why he was so aggressive. This old bull was missing some teeth and what he had left on his molars he had worn down over an inch. Remember, in the wild nothing dies of old age. The PH estimated this bull to be around 40 years old. For a dry land hippo who spends most of his days fighting off lions that’s incredibly old. Usually they die a lot younger and never reach this level of maturity. We were all so pumped to take such an old beast. An arrow to the heart is a quick death an old warrior like this deserves VS being eaten alive by lions.

node.text: A true accomplishment of a lifetime! Giant ancient dry land hippo with a bow. This Extremely old aggressive bull was by far the most dangerous animal I’ve ever hunted. When we saw him, he was literally twice the size as all the other hippos. Judging by all his scars and old characteristics, we knew he was a true ancient Dinosaur past his prime and a perfect bull to try and hunt, but little did we know what we were signing up for 😳. Over the course of 3 days and we tracked this 1 specific hippo bull over 13 miles. The trackers were truly amazing to say the least, but his monstrous giant tracks stood out and made it easy to tell him apart from other hippos. Little did I know what was in store when we took up his track. This bull was so aggressive and so dominate when we got close he full on charged us and tried to to kill us. It was the most stressful situation I’ve ever been in my entire life. He charged us 5 times but thank god we got out of the way, and never had to shoot the hippo with a gun. But finally after 3 days of tracking this 1 bull we caught a break. We found him in a pool of water that had a steep slope on 1 side and a gradual slope on the other creating a natural place where we knew he would come out of the water.
